    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Ratings Improve</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Richard Sandomir</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Sandomir, Richard</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Fox Sports generated 15.2 overnight Nielsen rating for Game 2 of World Series on Sunday, down 4 percent from comparable game a year ago, but 9 percent above Game 1 rating (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Fox Sports generated a 15.2 overnight Nielsen rating for Game 2 of the World Series on Sunday, down 4 percent from the comparable Yankees-Braves game a year ago, but 9 percent above Saturday's Game 1 rating.</p>
        <p>Through two games, the average 14.6 rating is 5 percent below last year's.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Fox Sports generated a 15.2 overnight Nielsen rating for Game 2 of the World Series on Sunday, down 4 percent from the comparable Yankees-Braves game a year ago, but 9 percent above Saturday's Game 1 rating.</p>
        <p>Through two games, the average 14.6 rating is 5 percent below last year's.</p>
        <p>Each overnight rating point equals 675,000 television households.</p>
        <p>In the New York market, the game rated a 42.1, the highest-rated program in the area since the last ''Seinfeld'' two years ago. A second New York team in the World Series elevated the local Game 2 rating from a 32.7 last year.</p>
        <p>More important for Fox is that the rating in markets outside New York rose 13 percent compared with Game 1.</p>
        <p>Los Angeles generated a 13.5, Chicago a 9.8, Philadelphia an 11.2, San Francisco a 10.5 and Boston a 13.6.</p>
        <p>Richard Sandomir</p>
        <p>BASEBALL: SUBWAY SERIES -- NOTEBOOK</p>
      </block>
